# Rule: DDD Entity Encapsulation

For Entity classes, follow DDD encapsulation principles:

- Entity properties must use `private set;` (or `init;` only where truly immutable construction is intended).
- Do not expose public setters on core domain state.
- State changes must happen through domain methods with clear intent (e.g. `Activate()`, `Rename(name)`).
- Validate invariants inside constructor/factory and state-changing methods.
- Keep persistence concerns out of domain behavior.

## Example

```csharp
// ✅ Good
public class EntityName
{
    public int Id { get; private set; }
    public string Name { get; private set; }
    public bool IsActive { get; private set; }

    public EntityName(string name)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(name))
            throw new ArgumentException("Name is required.");

        Name = name.Trim();
        IsActive = false;
    }

    public void Activate() => IsActive = true;
}
```
